[2]
Date: 28 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_47.HTM#Sec12>

Foot & mouth disease in Brazil
Follow-up report No. 5
See also: 28 Oct 2005, 28 Oct 2005, 21 Oct 2005, 21 Oct 2005, 14 Oct 2005,
14 Oct 2005, 12 Nov 2004, 8 Oct 2004,
17 Sep 2004, 30 Jul 2004, 23 Jul 2004, 2 Jul 2004, 18 Jun 2004
Translation of information received on 22 and 26 Oct 2005 from Dr Jorge
Caetano Junior, Director, Department of Animal Protection (DDA), Ministry
of Agriculture, Livestock and Food Supply, Brasilia:
End of previous report period: 25 Oct 2005 (see Disease Information, 18
[43], 389, dated 28 Oct 2005).
End of this report period: 25 Oct 2005.
Precise identification of agent: foot and mouth disease (FMD) virus serotype O.
Date of first confirmation of the event: 8 Oct 2005.
Date of start of the event: 26 Sep 2005.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Details of new outbreaks (suspected):
First administrative division (State): Parana
Type of epidemiological unit: farm
Date of start of the event: 18 Oct 2005
Municipality: Amapora / Grandes Rios / Maringa / Loanda
Species: bov / bov / bov / bov, ovi
Number of animals in the (suspected) outbreaks:
susceptible: 1731 / 829 / 499 / 1112, 137
cases: 4 / 3 / 5 / 9, 0
deaths: zero in all cases
destroyed: zero in all cases
slaughtered: zero in all case
Description of affected populations: Nelore breed fattening cattle. 20
animals aged between 12 and 14 months and one animal aged over 36 months
have shown clinical signs of a vesicular disease.
The farms were first inspected on 18 Oct 2005 and it was found from the
registers that all the animals were vaccinated.
Diagnosis: these clinical suspicions are based on clinical signs suggestive
of a vesicular disease. Samples have been taken in all 4 farms and sent to
the National Agricultural Defense Laboratory
(LANAGRO-PA), Belem, Para.
Control measures
A. Undertaken:
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning.
B. To be undertaken:
- stamping out;
- disinfection of infected premises/establishments.
Other details/comments:
The suspect herds referred to in this report have in common the fact that
they all received animals that had been purchased at auction at Londrina
(State of Parana) on 4 Oct 2005. The epidemiological investigation
established a link between the sick animals and other animals originating
from Eldorado (State of Mato Grosso do Sul), a district where 2 outbreaks
of FMD due to virus serotype O had previously been reported(1). The other
farms that received animals purchased at the auction sales at Londrina have
been placed under surveillance. The animals on these farms do not currently
present any clinical signs of a vesicular disease.
Final report: no.
(1) See Immediate notification report, Follow-up report No. 1 and Follow-up
report No. 2
******
