<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/AIS_47.HTM#Sec12>

Foot & mouth disease in Brazil
Follow-up report No. 6
See also: 28 Oct 2005, 28 Oct 2005, 21 Oct 2005, 21 Oct 2005, 14 Oct 2005,
14 Oct 2005, 12 Nov 2004, 8 Oct 2004,
17 Sep 2004, 30 Jul 2004, 23 Jul 2004, 2 Jul 2004, 18 Jun 2004
Translation of information received on 26 Oct 2005 from Dr Jorge Caetano
Junior, Director, Department of Animal Protection (DDA), Ministry of
Agriculture, Livestock and Food Supply, Brasilia:
End of previous report period: 25 Oct 2005 (see Disease Information, 18
[43], 390, dated 28 Oct 2005).
End of this report period: 25 Oct 2005.
Precise identification of agent: foot and mouth disease (FMD) virus
serotype O.
Date of first confirmation of the event: 8 Oct 2005.
Date of start of the event: 26 Sep 2005.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Details of new outbreak:
First administrative division (State): Mato Grosso do Sul
Lower administrative division (municipality): Eldorado
Type of epidemiological unit: farm
Date of start of the outbreak: 12 Oct 2005
Species: bov, sui
Number of animals in the outbreak
susceptible/ cases/ deaths/ destroyed/ slaughtered
bov: 24/ 3/ 0/ 24/ 0
sui: 41/ 0/ 0/ 41/ 0
The owner of the affected farm notified the official Veterinary Service of
the outbreak on 19 Oct 2005.
Description of affected population: fattening cattle. There have been no
reports of suspected cases in species other than bovines.
Diagnosis:
Laboratory where diagnostic tests were performed: National Agricultural
Defence Laboratory (LANAGRO-PA), Belem, Para
Species examined: bov
Diagnostic tests used: indirect sandwich ELISA(1) (using epithelium)
Date: 22 Oct 2005
Results: positive
Source of outbreak: unknown or inconclusive (investigations in progress).
A. Undertaken:
- stamping out;
- quarantine;
- movement control inside the country;
- screening;
- zoning.
B. To be undertaken: disinfection.
Final report: no.
(1) ELISA: enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[FMD is continuing to spread in Brazil. This sad disease has had a major
impact on the exports of animal/animal products from Brazil. Many countries
have placed bans on these products, which is having a tremendous economic
impact, as well as caused the destruction of large numbers of animals. This
also takes an emotional toll on producers, veterinarians, and all involved.
- Mod.TG]
